# Events over polling

**Default:** Do not mirror or refresh state on a **repeating** schedule when the stack already tells you **when** it changed. Wire the **event** (signal, property change, lifecycle hook) and update once at that point.

This applies to **UI sync** (tooltips, labels, enablement), **cache invalidation**, **scans** (“walk widgets / re-read mpv every N ms”), and **retry loops** — not only generic “state mirroring.”

## Use events first

| Layer | Prefer |
|-------|--------|
| **GTK / libadwaita** | `connect_*` signals, action `activate`, `notify::*` on GObject properties, `PropertyBinding`, controllers (click, scroll, key) |
| **GIO / GLib** | async completion, `FileMonitor`, `Application` / `ActionGroup` signals — not a timer to “see if something changed” |
| **libmpv** | `observe_property` for properties you care about; `set_wakeup_callback` only to **schedule main-thread work**; drain with `wait_event(0)` on the main thread. **Never** call other mpv APIs inside the wakeup callback |
| **Product lifecycle** | `FileLoaded`, `path` change, popover `show`, user selection, chapter scrub finish — refresh derived UI **there**, not on a global tick |

## Periodic refresh is not the default

```rust
// ❌ BAD — tooltip/header drifts or races; hides missing event wiring
glib::timeout_add_local(Duration::from_secs(1), move || {
    sync_audio_tooltip(&ctx);
    glib::ControlFlow::Continue
});

// ✅ GOOD — key points only (after restore, path change, popover open, user pick)
audio_tracks::refresh_audio_tooltip_for_player(&ctx.player, &ctx.widgets.vol_menu);
```

```rust
// ❌ BAD — scan every tick for work that has a signal
glib::timeout_add_local(interval, move || {
    if popover.is_visible() { rebuild_rows(); }
    glib::ControlFlow::Continue
});

// ✅ GOOD
popover.connect_show(move |_| rebuild_rows());
```

## One-shot deferral ≠ polling

A **single** `glib::idle_add_local_once` or **bounded** retry chain **tied to one event** (e.g. one idle after `FileLoaded` so `track-list` can settle) is fine. It runs because **that** load happened, not on a clock.

Do **not** promote it to `timeout_add_local` / `interval` unless you document why events are insufficient.

## When a timer is still OK

Only when:

- There is **no** reliable event (or the API documents a tick), **or**
- Product accepts **coarser** updates and observation would be costly.

If you add a timer:

1. **Comment why** subscriptions or lifecycle hooks were insufficient (file + symbol).
2. Use the **largest interval** UX allows.
3. Do **not** copy legacy ticks (e.g. transport UI) when touching that area — replace with events where straightforward.

## Agent checklist (new sync / refresh code)

- [ ] Listed the **observable change** (user action, mpv property, load milestone).
- [ ] Wired **that** event (or one bounded follow-up to it), not a repeating timer.
- [ ] UI derived from mpv/GTK state updates on **open**, **select**, **load**, **path** — not every second “just in case.”
- [ ] No new `timeout_add*` / `interval` / busy main-thread loop without the “When a timer is still OK” justification.
